        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-06-25T13:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-06-25T12:20:00-05:00" n="199"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d199">
                <head>199. Notes of Meeting<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d199fn1">Source:
                            <persName>Johnson</persName> Library, Tom Johnson’s Notes of Meetings,
                        June 25, 1968–1:20 p.m.-Tuesday luncheon. Top Secret. Drafted by Tom
                        Johnson.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1968-06-25T13:20:00-04:00" to="1968-06-25T14:35:00-04:00">June 25,
                            1968, 1:20–2:35 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">NOTES OF THE PRESIDENT’S MEETING WITH TUESDAY LUNCHEON GROUP</p>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>THOSE ATTENDING THE MEETING WERE</head>
                    <item>The President</item>
                    <item>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_CCM1">Clifford</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss> Director <persName corresp="#p_HRM1"
                            >Helms</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_WGEG1">Wheeler</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>General Taylor</item>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>George Christian</item>
                    <item>Tom Johnson</item>
                </list>
                <p>[Here follows discussion unrelated to the Middle East.]</p>
                <p rend="center">MIDDLE EAST</p>
                <p>The <persName>President</persName>: George <persName corresp="#p_BGW1"
                        >Ball</persName> is our Middle East man.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>: We’re getting in a trap
                    in the Middle East. <persName corresp="#p_JG1">Jarring</persName> will come back
                    with nothing.</p>
                <p>The Russians and the <gloss target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss> will come back into the
                    Security Council asking for sanction.</p>
                <p>If we veto, we’re dead in the Middle East. I cannot today give you a
                    proposal.</p>
                <p>An American position must be made. It will take intense diplomacy.</p>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>: The British
                    want us to take joint initiative.</p>
                <p>The <persName>President</persName>: Aren’t they in a deep internal crisis?</p>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>: Yes. To push
                    them may create a crisis in their Cabinet.</p>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>: You may want
                    to send Arthur (Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_GAJ1">Goldberg</persName>) to
                    Tel Aviv.</p>
                <pb facs="0417" n="389" xml:id="pg_389"/>
                <p>The <persName>President</persName>: Would he go?</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>: He would go.</p>
                <p>The <persName>President</persName>: I am against the trip. Can’t you give
                        <persName corresp="#p_JG1">Jarring</persName> some imaginative
                    innovations?</p>
                <p>What about <persName corresp="#p_BLD1">Battle</persName> or <persName
                        corresp="#p_SJJ1">Sisco</persName>?</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>: <persName
                        corresp="#p_BLD1">Battle</persName> was Ambassador to the <gloss
                        target="#t_UAR1">UAR</gloss>.</p>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>: Sisco would be
                    good.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>: <persName
                        corresp="#p_JG1">Jarring</persName> is a poor guy to work with. He won’t
                    push anybody.</p>
                <p>The <persName>President</persName>: What about Vance?</p>
                <p>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_KNB1">Katzenbach</persName>: He would be
                    fine. Also McGeorge Bundy would be good.<note n="2" xml:id="d199fn2">In his
                        notes on this meeting, <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt Rostow</persName>
                        summed up the discussion on the Middle East as “some indecisive talk.” He
                        added: “Will talk about it when Sec. <persName corresp="#p_RD1"
                            >Rusk</persName> gets back.” (Ibid., National Security File, Files of
                            <persName corresp="#p_RWW1">Walt W. Rostow</persName>, Meetings with the
                        President, May-June 1968)</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follows discussion unrelated to the Middle East.]</p>
            </div>
